&gt; Are there any coding projects similar to NEAT, in its generalized
&gt; ability, but more like the brain&#39;s &quot;live&quot; learning?

No one knows in detail how learning works in the brain.  We don&#39;t know
how most things are represented, or how those representations get
updated.  All we have right now are highly simplified models at various
levels of abstraction, but we know that these are inadequate.

Don&#39;t be misled by computer scientists who give simple learning
mechanisms fancy biological names, like &quot;neural network&quot; or &quot;genetic
algorithm&quot;.  These are highly simplified and abstract mathematical
constructs compared to the complicated and messy biological phenomena
they are named after.  It&#39;s like the difference between the hypothetical
canonball&#39;s simple 1D trajectory in a vacuum, vs. a real world
knuckleball whose spin and trajectory can only be explained using vector
calculus and fluid dynamics.

So to answer your original question: no, we don&#39;t have a general purpose
learning rule that works like the brain, because we don&#39;t understand how
the brain works.

And although brains have very powerful learning algorithms, they also
have a lot of built-in structure that is present from birth.  Most
machine learning algorithms start out with zero weights, or initial
random weights, not the incredibly detailed structure produced by our
genes through the process of fetal development.  So don&#39;t think that
some simple learning algorithm is going to provide the &quot;magic bullet&quot;
that produces intelligent machines.  It&#39;s not going to be that easy.  It
took evolution a long time to come up with the structure of the
mammalian brain.  And it&#39;s going to take us another century or two to
figure out how it works.

